Log transform

Zihan Fang

10/9/2020

1 Introduction

In this blog, I will answer a series of questions related to the transformation of data. I will use both analytic methods and simulation to answer the questions.

1.1 Background

It is common in the analysis of biological data to log transform data representing concentrations or data representing dose response.

2 Methods

2.1 Part 1

  • For each distribution below, generate a figure of the PDF and CDF. Mark the mean and median in the figure.

    XGAMMA(shape=3,scale=1)

sha=3
sca=1
x=seq(0,10,by=0.1)

pdf=dgamma(x, shape=sha,scale = sca)
mean.gam = sha*sca
median.gam = qgamma(0.5,shape=sha,scale=sca)
plot(x,pdf,main  = "PDF of the Gamma Dist",type = "l")
abline (v=mean.gam,col="red")
abline (v=median.gam,col="blue")

t=seq(0,10,by=0.1)
cdf=pgamma(t, shape=sha,scale = sca)
mean.gam = sha*sca
median.gam = qgamma(0.5,shape=sha,scale=sca)
plot(t,cdf,main  = "CDF of the Gamma Dist",type = "l")
abline (v=mean.gam,col="red")
abline (v=median.gam,col="blue")
legend("topleft",c("Median","Mean"), col = c("blue","red"), lwd = 1, bty = "n")

To draw figures of the PDF and CDF of GAMMA(shape=3,scale=1), I first assign x a sequence randomly, then I use dgamma to plot PDF and pgamma to plot CDF. I use the method shape*scale to calculate the mean of GAMMA(shape=3,scale=1), and qgamma to get the median.

*X*LOG NORMAL(**=1,**=1)

pdf=dlnorm(x,-1,1)
mean.log = exp(-1+1^2/2)
median.log = qlnorm(0.5,-1,1)
plot(x,pdf,main  = "PDF of LOG NORMAL Dist",type = "l")
abline (v=mean.log,col="red")
abline (v=median.log,col="blue")
legend("topright",c("Median","Mean"), col = c("blue","red"), lwd = 1, bty = "n")

t=seq(0,15,by=0.1)
cdf=plnorm(t,-1,1)
plot(t,cdf,main  = "CDF of LOG NORMAL Dist",type = "l")
abline (v=mean.log,col="red")
abline (v=median.log,col="blue")
legend("topright",c("Median","Mean"), col = c("blue","red"), lwd = 1, bty = "n")

To draw figures of the PDF and CDF of LOG NORMAL(=1,=1), I first assign x a sequence randomly, then I use dlnorm to plot PDF and plnorm to plot CDF. I use the method exp(2/2+) to calculate the mean of LOG NORMAL(=1,=1), and exp() to get the median.

abline (v=mean.uni,col="red")
abline (v=median.uni,col="blue")
legend("topleft",c("Median","Mean"), col = c("blue","red"), lwd = 1, bty = "n")

mean.uni = (0+12)/2
median.uni = (0+12)/2
plot(t,cdf,main  = "CDF of UNIFORM Dist",type = "l")
abline (v=mean.uni,col="red")
abline (v=median.uni,col="blue")
legend("topleft",c("Median","Mean"), col = c("blue","red"), lwd = 1, bty = "n")

To draw figures of the PDF and CDF of UNIFORM(0,12), and we can know min=0, max=12. First, I assign x a sequence randomly which should bigger than 12, then I use dunif to plot PDF and punif to plot CDF. I use the method (min+max)/2 to calculate the mean of UNIFORM(0,12), and (min+max)/2 to get the median.

  • For each of the distributions below, generate 1000 samples of size 100. For each sample, calculate the geometric and arithmetic mean. Generate a scatter plot of the geometic and arithmetic sample means. Add the line of identify as a reference line.

art.mean=NA
geo.mean=NA
for(i in 1:1000){
  d=rgamma(n=100,shape = sha,scale = sca)
  art.mean[i]=mean(d)
  geo.mean[i]=exp(mean(log(d)))
}

plot(geo.mean,art.mean)
abline(0,1)

2.2 Part 2

Show that if Xi>0 for all i, then the arithmetic mean is greater than or equal to the geometric mean.

Hint: Start with the sample mean of the transformation Yi=log(Xi).

art.mean=NA
geo.mean=NA
N<-200
M<-10000
for(i in 1:M){
  d=sample(N,M,replace = TRUE)
  art.mean[i]=mean(d)
  geo.mean[i]=exp(mean(log(d)))
}
unique(ifelse(geo.mean <= art.mean, "arithmetic mean is greater than or equal to the geometric mean." , "geometric mean is greater than arithmetic mean." ))
## [1] "arithmetic mean is greater than or equal to the geometric mean."

For this question, I use simulation method to prove if Xi>0 for all i, the sample size is 10000 and if arithmetic mean is greater, the code will return arithmetic mean is greater than or equal to the geometric mean. I also use the unique() to eliminate duplicate results. Then result shows that the arithmetic mean is always greater than or equal to the geometric mean.

2.3 Part 3

What is the correct relationship between E[log(X)] and log(E[X])? Is one always larger? Equal? Explain your answer.

ElX=NA
lEX=NA
N<-200
M<-10000

for (i in 1:M) {
  X<-sample(N,M,replace = TRUE)
  ElX[i]<-mean(log(X))
  lEX[i]<-log(mean(X))
}

unique(ifelse(ElX <= lEX, "E[log(X)] is smaller than or equal to log(E[X])" , "E[log(X)] is bigger than log(E[X])" ))
## [1] "E[log(X)] is smaller than or equal to log(E[X])"

In this part, the correct relationship between E[log(X)] and log(E[X]) is that E[log(X)] is smaller than or equal to log(E[X]). I use simulation method to calculate the relationship between E[log(X)] and log(E[X]), the number of studies is 10000(M) and the size for each study is 200(N). ElX stands for E[log(X)] and lEX stands for log(E[X]). Then I use ifelse function to verify the relationship between E[log(X)] and log(E[X]), if E[log(X)] <= log(E[X]), the code will return E[log(X)] is smaller than or equal to log(E[X]). After I run the code, we can find it return E[log(X)] is smaller than or equal to log(E[X]) 10000 times. Finally, I use unique() to eliminate duplicate results.

To find if this result is correct for any X, we can change the value assigned to M into any number we want, and we can find that it always returns that E[log(X)] is smaller than or equal to log(E[X]).
